Utterances.UttText: S: Middle aged woman presenting with several hours of severe 10/10, sharp, constant abdominal pain that started in the epigastric region radiating to her back and has spread to her entire abdomen.

Phrases.PhraseText: Middle aged woman presenting with several hours of severe 10/10,
started in the epigastric region radiating

Utterances.UttText: She vomited once at midnight before arriving at the ED and has not eaten since.
PMH significant for HTN, HLD, 45 pack year smoking history, drinks alcohol daily.
She is sweaty, has chills and a fever.
Review of systems negative for chest pain, headache, hematuria, hematochezia, diarrhea, constipation, muscle weakness, weight loss or gain, dysuria.
Lives with her husband who brought her to the ED.
O: Febrile, hypotension, tachycardia PE:  General: Patient is awake, alert, supine on exam table, appears distressed and in pain.
Abdominal Exam: No visible scars, rashes or deformities.
Abdomen is soft, tender to light palpation in all four quadrants.
Chest and Lung: No murmurs, rubs or gallops.
Lungs clear to auscultation BL Extremities: Warm and well perfused.
Radial pulses 2+ bilaterally  A: Middle aged woman presenting with acute onset of severe epigastric pain radiating to her back, fever, anorexia and vomiting consistent with acute pancreatitis.

Phrases.PhraseText: Middle aged woman presenting with acute onset of severe epigastric pain radiating

Utterances.UttText: PMH significant for HTN, HLD, smoking history and daily alcohol use and physical exam notable for diffuse abdominal pain.

Other differentials to rule out: gastroenteritis, appendicitis, diverticulitis, peptic ulcer Plan:  -Admit to floor  -Start IV Morphine, obtain RUQ ultrasound, obtain CBC, BMP, Lipase, Amylase, GGT,  -keep patient NPO, give zofran as needed for nausea

MappingCandidates.CandidatePreferred: Stage IV Uveal Melanoma AJCC v7
Structure of right upper quadrant of abdomen
